### Selected 3D models for STEAM lessons we tried ourselves

Our team combed through online 3D model databases to find some interesting projects for various school subjects. We tested them ourselves, then rated their difficulty on a scale from easy (⭐) to very demanding (⭐⭐⭐).

Total print time and PLA filament usage were estimated with optimal settings for the Flashforge Adventurer 4 printer. One meter of 1.75 mm PLA filament weighs about 2.98 grams, and a 1 kg spool contains approximately 335 meters.

**Biology**

Indeed, with a 3D printer you can print a model of an animal or plant cell and show it to students. For biology and nature lessons, you can print much more: models of internal organs, bones, or even a complete skeleton – life-sized! Of course, this requires a lot of time, and if you care about anatomical accuracy, the print settings must be perfectly calibrated.

(3D printed model for school: cell)

Interestingly, such models are increasingly being used at universities too, alongside real specimens.

- [Plant cell](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-multi-color-mini-plant-cell-60821) ⭐⭐ – print time: 4 hr 40 min; filament: 17.5 m; other supplies: glue;
- [Animal cell](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2803322) ⭐⭐ – print time: 4 hr; filament: 12.5 m; other supplies: glue;
- [Human heart model](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-anatomical-heart-34709) ⭐⭐ – print time: 15 hr; filament: 13.02 m;
- [Human skull model](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4830026) ⭐⭐⭐ – print time: ~40+ hr; filament: 165 m; other supplies: glue, magnets, drill;

**Mathematics**

3D props can be used to illustrate math principles – especially geometry. When students struggle to visualize a solid in space, like a regular icosahedron, just hand them one.

- [Regular icosahedron](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1343285/files) ⭐ – (300% scale) print time: 30 min; filament: 2 m;
- [Pythagorean theorem](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:245202/) ⭐⭐ – print time: 3 hr; filament: 11 m;

**Geography**

(3D printed model for school: map of Europe)

The Earth isn’t flat – which is definitely worth showing students. Our planet’s landscape is highly diverse, and its canyons, volcanoes, cliffs, and other natural features can be illustrated with 3D props.

- [Volcanoes of the world](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1316498) ⭐ – print time: ~30 min to 3 hr each; filament: ~1.5 m to 11 m each
- [Topographic map of Europe](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5147240) ⭐⭐ – (80% scale) print time: 4 hr 20 min; filament: 8 m;
- [Grand Canyon erosion](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2709566) ⭐⭐⭐ – base print time: 12 hr; filament: 29 m PLA + 10 m PVA; other supplies: 2L bottle, craft knife, screwdriver, tape;

**Physics**

Although physics deals with the fundamental interactions and properties of our world, learning it often boils down to theory alone. With 3D props, you can show that physics is all around us, and that its theories are based on real phenomena. And if we’re in the mood to introduce students to the cosmos while undertaking a really ambitious project, you can print and assemble a model of the Solar System.

- [Balancing bird](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-spinning-balancing-bird-6401) ⭐⭐ – print time: 2 hr 35 min; filament: 7 m;
- [Solar System](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-model-solar-system-5505) ⭐⭐ – print time: 35+ hr; filament: ~25 m;
- [Sun–Earth–Moon Planetarium](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3928677/files) ⭐⭐⭐ – print time: 35+ hr; filament: ~21 m; other supplies: screws and nuts;

**History**

(3D printed model for school: paleolithic hand axe)

Among 3D printing enthusiasts, there are many fans of ancient and modern history, thanks to whom we have lots of high-quality ready-made models. The highly detailed ones usually cost money, but are often worth it – especially to see students marvel at the ingenuity of their ancestors.

- [Statue of Sekhmet](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-sekhmet-96018) ⭐ – print time: 3 hr 10 min; filament: 11 m
- [Paleolithic hand axe](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-stone-handaxe-81793) ⭐⭐ – print time: 6 hr; filament: 19 m;
- [Colosseum](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:962416/) ⭐⭐ – print time: 18 hr 30 min; filament: 36 m;

**Art**

Although 3D printers are more associated with engineering than art, when combined with design software, they can be effectively used to create original works. Moreover, you can print famous sculptures, monuments, and reliefs – much to the surprise of ancient masters.

- [Easter Island Moai](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-moai-head-on-easter-island-200530) ⭐ – print time: 2 hr; filament: 6 m;
- [Famous Parisian buildings](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:311002) ⭐ – print time: 30 min to 4 hr 30 min each; filament: 0.7 m to 11 m each;
- [Bust of Helena](https://www.myminifactory.com/object/3d-print-plaster-bust-of-helen-124529) ⭐⭐ – (50% scale) print time: 5 hr; filament: 14.2 m;
